recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2021 Porsche Taycan Turbo, Taycan Turbo S, Taycan, Taycan 4S, 911 Turbo S Coupe, Cayman, Cayman T, Cayman S, Cayman GT4, 911 Carrera Coupe, 911 Carrera S Coupe, 911 Carrera 4S Coupe, 911 Carrera 4S Targa, 911 Carrera Cabriolet, 911 Carrera S Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4S Targa Heritage Design Edition, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, 911 Turbo Coupe, 911 Turbo Cabriolet, 911 Turbo S Cabriolet, 718 Spyder, and Boxster vehicles.  Certain suspension components may not have been tightened correctly and can loosen.
recalls.Consequence: Loose suspension components may detach, causing a sudden loss of vehicle stability and control, and increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will replace the affected suspension nuts and bolts.  Dealers will also inspect surrounding components for damage, and replace any damaged parts as necessary.  Repairs will be performed free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed May 7, 2021. Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AMA3.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2021 911 Carrera Coupe, 911 Carrera S Coupe, 911 Carrera 4 Coupe, 911 Carrera 4S Coupe, 911 Turbo Coupe, 911 Turbo S Coupe, Panamera, Panamera 4 E-Hybrid, Panamera 4S, Panamera GTS, Panamera Turbo S, Taycan, Taycan 4S, Taycan Turbo, and Taycan Turbo S vehicles.  The seat belt automatic locking retractors may deactivate early, which can prevent the child restraint system from securing properly.  As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard number 208, "Occupant Crash Protection."
recalls.Consequence: An unsecured child restraint system can increase the risk of injury during a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will inspect and replace the seat belt assemblies, as necessary, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed October 1, 2021.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AMB6.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2021 911 Turbo Coupe, 911 Turbo S Coupe, 911 Carrera 4S Targa, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, 911 Turbo S Cabriolet, and 911 Turbo Cabriolet vehicles.  Incorrect passenger seat was installed and may cause a Occupant Classification System (OCS) malfunction.
recalls.Consequence: An OCS malfunction may affect the front passenger air bag, increasing the risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will install the correct seat, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed November 16, 2021.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AMB3.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2020-2024 911 vehicles.  The front windshield and rear window may not be properly secured and can detach.
recalls.Consequence: During air bag deployment, an unsecured windshield may not support the front air bags as intended, increasing the risk of injury in a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will inspect and replace the windshield and rear window as necessary, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed on August 30, 2024.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is ARA3.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2025 Panamera, 2024 718 Cayman GT4 RS, 718 Spyder RS, and 2021-2024 911 vehicles.  The center lock wheel bolt may fracture and cause the wheel to detach.
recalls.Consequence: Wheel detachment can result in a loss of vehicle control, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Owners should not drive their vehicles until they have been repaired.  Dealers will check the center lock wheel fastening system and replace any incorrectly manufactured parts, as necessary, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed on January 24, 2024.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is ARC4.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153) or go to nhtsa.gov.

recalls.Component: BACK OVER PREVENTION: SENSING SYSTEM: CAMERA
recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2019-2025 Cayenne, Cayenne E-Hybrid, 2020-2025 911, Taycan, 2024-2025 Panamera, and 2025 Panamera E-Hybrid vehicles. The rearview camera image may not display when the vehicle is placed in reverse. As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (FMVSS) number 111, "Rear Visibility."
recalls.Consequence: A rearview image that does not display properly reduces the driver's view behind the vehicle, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will update the driver assistance software, free of charge. Interim letters, notifying owners of the safety risk, are expected to be mailed February 16, 2026. Additional letters will be sent once the final remedy is available. Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243. Porsche's number for this recall is ASB2. Vehicle Identification Numbers (VINs) involved in this recall will be searchable on NHTSA.gov beginning January 19, 2026.

issues.title: PDK Transmission Overheating in Track Use
issues.description: PDK transmission experiences overheating during extended track sessions, leading to limp mode activation and potential transmission damage. Issue primarily affects vehicles with PDK option during high-performance driving.
issues.fix_description: Installation of additional transmission coolers, transmission fluid change, and potential transmission rebuild in severe cases
issues.prevention: Allow proper cool-down periods during track use, consider transmission cooler upgrade before track events

issues.title: Front Axle Lift System Failure
issues.description: Front axle lift system fails to operate properly, with the system not raising or lowering the front end as commanded. Can leave vehicle stuck in raised or lowered position.
issues.fix_description: Replacement of lift system hydraulic components, software updates, and system recalibration
issues.prevention: Regular system operation and maintenance, avoid excessive use on rough surfaces

issues.title: Excessive Tire Wear on Front Axle
issues.description: Premature and uneven tire wear on front tires, particularly on the inner edge. Issue related to aggressive alignment settings and track-focused suspension geometry.
issues.fix_description: Tire rotation, alignment adjustment, potential suspension geometry modifications
issues.prevention: Regular tire rotation, alignment checks, avoiding aggressive curb contact

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Body Panel Cracking
issues.description: Stress cracks developing in carbon fiber body panels, particularly around mounting points and high-stress areas. Most commonly affects front splitter and rear wing components.
issues.fix_description: Carbon fiber panel replacement or professional repair, reinforcement of mounting points
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive downforce loads, careful parking to prevent scraping, regular inspection

issues.title: Engine Knock Sensor False Readings
issues.description: Knock sensors providing false positive readings, causing the ECU to retard timing unnecessarily and reduce engine performance. Issue particularly noticeable during spirited driving.
issues.fix_description: Knock sensor replacement, ECU software update, engine recalibration
issues.prevention: Use high-quality fuel, regular engine maintenance, avoid lugging the engine

issues.title: Brake Pedal Vibration at High Speeds
issues.description: Brake pedal vibration and pulsation during high-speed braking, caused by brake disc warping or uneven pad deposits. Issue more prevalent with track use.
issues.fix_description: Brake disc replacement or resurfacing, brake pad replacement, proper bedding procedure
issues.prevention: Proper brake bedding, cool-down periods during track use, high-quality brake components

issues.title: Rear Wing Hydraulic System Leaks
issues.description: Hydraulic fluid leaks in the rear wing adjustment system, causing wing positioning issues and potential staining of vehicle surfaces.
issues.fix_description: Hydraulic seal replacement, system flush, component replacement if necessary
issues.prevention: Regular system inspection, avoid manual wing adjustment, proper storage

issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing and Crashes
issues.description: PCM infotainment system experiences frequent freezing, crashes, and slow response times. System may require hard resets to restore functionality.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, system reset, potential hardware replacement in severe cases
issues.prevention: Regular software updates, avoid overloading system with multiple apps

issues.title: Oil Temperature Sensor Malfunction
issues.description: Oil temperature sensors providing inaccurate readings, leading to incorrect temperature displays and potential engine protection system activation.
issues.fix_description: Oil temperature sensor replacement, wiring harness inspection, ECU updates
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid overheating, proper warm-up procedures

issues.title: Center Lock Wheel Corrosion
issues.description: Corrosion developing on center lock wheel mechanisms, potentially affecting wheel removal and installation. Issue more common in areas with road salt exposure.
issues.fix_description: Center lock mechanism cleaning, lubrication, replacement if severely corroded
issues.prevention: Regular cleaning, anti-seize compound application, avoid salt exposure when possible

editorial.tagline: Pure naturally aspirated perfection meets modern precision
editorial.hero_blurb: The 992 GT3 represents the pinnacle of naturally aspirated sports car engineering, delivering a 4.0-liter flat-six that screams to 9,000 RPM. This is Porsche's love letter to driving purists, wrapped in cutting-edge aerodynamics and chassis technology.
editorial.essence: The GT3 is the last great naturally aspirated 911, combining a race-bred 4.0L flat-six with precision-tuned aerodynamics and suspension. It's the ultimate expression of Porsche's racing DNA translated for the road, offering an uncompromised driving experience that bridges the gap between street and track.
editorial.heritage: Born from decades of 911 evolution and direct GT3 Cup racing experience, the 992 GT3 carries forward the lineage established in 1999. Each generation has refined the formula of lightweight construction, aerodynamic efficiency, and naturally aspirated power, with the 992 representing the most sophisticated iteration yet.
editorial.design_philosophy: Every line serves aerodynamic function while maintaining 911 DNA. The massive rear wing, front splitter, and side air intakes aren't just for show—they generate significant downforce while cooling the high-revving engine. The design balances aggression with elegance, creating visual drama that matches the performance.
editorial.motorsport_history: Direct descendant of the 911 GT3 Cup racer and RSR, sharing engine architecture and aerodynamic lessons learned from countless track victories. The GT3's development is intrinsically linked to Porsche's motorsport program, with engineers constantly refining the formula based on racing feedback.
editorial.engine_character: The 4.0L naturally aspirated flat-six is a masterpiece of engineering emotion, delivering linear power that builds relentlessly to a spine-tingling 9,000 RPM redline. Throttle response is instantaneous, with none of the lag associated with forced induction—just pure, unfiltered connection between right foot and rear wheels.
editorial.transmission_feel: The PDK dual-clutch shifts with surgical precision, delivering lightning-fast gear changes that perfectly complement the engine's high-rev nature. Manual mode transforms the transmission into an extension of your will, while the optional manual gearbox offers the ultimate in driver engagement for purists.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Razor-sharp precision meets surprising compliance, with the GT3's chassis providing telepathic communication between driver and road. The suspension manages to be both track-capable and street-livable, offering remarkable body control without punishing ride quality.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulically assisted steering delivers pure, unfiltered feedback from the front wheels with perfect weighting that builds naturally with speed. Every nuance of the road surface transmits through the wheel, creating an intimate connection that makes the GT3 feel like an extension of the driver.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive carbon-ceramic discs provide fade-free stopping power with a firm, progressive pedal feel. The brakes inspire complete confidence whether scrubbing speed for a tight corner or managing repeated track sessions, with excellent modulation throughout the pedal travel.
editorial.sound_signature: A symphony of mechanical music that builds from a purposeful idle growl to a spine-tingling wail at redline. The flat-six's distinctive boxer rumble combines with intake honk and exhaust roar to create one of the automotive world's most intoxicating soundtracks.
editorial.ideal_owner: Track day enthusiasts and driving purists who appreciate naturally aspirated engines and want the ultimate expression of 911 performance. Perfect for those who value driver engagement over luxury amenities and understand the significance of what may be the last great NA sports car.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Daily commuters seeking comfort, luxury-focused buyers wanting extensive amenities, or those uncomfortable with the GT3's uncompromising nature and track-focused character. Also not suitable for those seeking fuel efficiency or whisper-quiet highway cruising.
editorial.buyers_summary: The 992 GT3 represents a pinnacle moment in automotive history—potentially the last naturally aspirated 911 GT3. Values are likely to remain strong given its significance and limited production. Focus on finding examples with desirable options and verified maintenance history.

pros: Exceptional braking stability with 50% less nose dive
Perfect steering feedback and precision
Improved suspension with reduced bump stops for better travel
Naturally aspirated 4.0L engine that revs to 9,000 RPM
Track-focused capabilities while remaining street drivable

Manual transmission option in Touring model
Makes driver feel more confident and skilled
cons: $40,000 price increase from previous generation ($185k to $220k)
Not the fastest 0-60 in 911 lineup at 3.2 seconds
Less torque than previous generation
Manual transmission cruises at high RPM on highway (noisy)
Carbon fiber bucket seats uncomfortable for street driving
Carbon fiber roll cage not available in US market
expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 GT3 is described as the best GT3 Porsche has ever made, successfully fulfilling its mission as a car you can drive to the track, at the track, and home again. While not the fastest 911 in straight-line acceleration, it excels in cornering and track performance. The $40,000 price increase makes it harder to justify for existing 992.1 owners, but it remains exceptional for those wanting a race car that non-race drivers can handle at the limit.

expertReviews.title: 2025 Porsche 911 GT3 First Drive Review: Somehow EVEN BETTER?!
pros: 4L naturally aspirated flat-6 engine revving to 9,000 RPM
Incredible steering feel
Improved suspension setup that's softer but more balanced
New shorter gear ratios (8% lower) make power more accessible
Anti-dive system improves corner balance
More suspension travel with shorter bump stops
New Weissach package available
Excellent track and road capability
cons: Torque is down due to environmental regulations
New exhaust with four catalytic converters changes sound character
Expensive starting price around $245,000 CAD
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 Porsche 911 GT3 represents incremental but meaningful improvements over its predecessor. While power remains at 502 hp and torque is actually reduced due to regulations, Porsche compensated with shorter gear ratios that make the car more accessible and engaging to drive. The revised suspension is softer yet more balanced, with better bump stop design and anti-dive geometry. The magical naturally aspirated engine experience remains intact, making this an even better GT3 than before.

More accelerative than previous model despite less torque
Brilliant naturally aspirated engine that revs to 9000 RPM
Shorter gear ratios improve usability
Consistent performance after multiple track laps
Available with rear seats in Touring variant
Good value at £157,300
cons: More engine noise on motorway and everyday driving

expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 GT3 represents a massive leap forward for the GT3, feeling far more effective on track than its predecessor. With outstanding stability, grip, and steering precision, it delivers phenomenal performance both on track and road. The revised suspension geometry and shorter gear ratios make it more accelerative and involving to drive. At £157,300, it remains excellent value for a naturally aspirated masterpiece that may not exist much longer due to emissions regulations.

expertReviews.title: The NEW 992.2 GT3 and GT3 Touring on Road & Track! - TheSmokingTire
pros: Exceptional ride quality and comfort improved from previous generation
Outstanding steering precision and communication between driver and car
Naturally aspirated 502hp engine maintains performance while improving emissions compliance
New folding bucket seats allow rear passenger access in Touring model
Shorter gear ratios (8% across the board) improve acceleration feel
Lightweight Weissach package saves 48 lbs with carbon components
Track performance improved with better aerodynamic balance and anti-dive suspension
Manual transmission maintains engaging driving experience
cons: Higher highway RPM due to shorter gearing affects fuel economy

expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 GT3 represents a masterful evolution that addresses previous criticisms while maintaining the car's essential character. Porsche has successfully improved ride quality, steering consistency, and environmental compliance without sacrificing the engaging, naturally aspirated driving experience. The Touring with Weissach package emerges as potentially the most desirable variant, offering improved daily usability while retaining track capability. This remains the gold standard for engaging with machinery in the modern world.

expertReviews.title: Porsche 911 992.2 GT3 Review: The Last Naturally Aspirated 911?
pros: Exceptional naturally aspirated flat-6 engine with 9000 RPM capability
Outstanding driving dynamics and track capability in all conditions
Pure driving experience that teaches and improves piloting skills
More exciting character with shortened gear ratios and reduced sound insulation
Improved stability during braking phases
cons: No power increase compared to previous generation
Heavier than predecessor due to additional catalytic converters
Price increased by €15,000 with €50,000+ for lightweight options
Very firm suspension unsuitable for daily comfort
Loud interior requiring raised voices for conversation
expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 GT3 doesn't progress in performance and becomes heavier, but surprisingly feels more exciting thanks to chassis refinements and acoustic changes. While too radical for some with its firm suspension and constant flat-6 buzz, it remains exceptional for pure driving pleasure. However, at €15,000 more expensive plus costly options, and potentially being the last naturally aspirated Porsche due to Euro 7 regulations, it's both celebration-worthy and heartbreaking as an irreplaceable piece of automotive passion.

expertReviews.title: Brilliant new "992.2" Porsche 911 GT3 tested on track and road
pros: Exceptional track and road versatility
Excellent suspension with 25mm more travel and improved ride quality
Beautiful steering feel - more linear and precise than previous generation
Thrives on revs with 9000 RPM redline
Great balance and mid-corner speed
Can be enjoyed at sensible speeds on back roads
Refined daily sports car capabilities with comfort features
cons: Torque reduced by 20 Nm due to emissions regulations
Short gearing makes motorway conversations 'shouty'
Weight increased by 20kg
Limited production means fewer available than demand
High price at £150,000 plus options
expertReviews.verdict: Another terrific GT3 that successfully bridges track and road use. The 992.2 generation addresses previous steering concerns with more linear, precise feel while maintaining the thrilling 9000 RPM naturally aspirated engine. Despite slight torque reduction and increased weight from emissions compliance, shorter gearing compensates for performance. The improved suspension with extra travel enhances both track capability and road comfort. This is one of the few cars that truly excels as both a daily driver and track weapon, offering the rare combination of usability and pure driving engagement.
